side effects.
A possible programming error in C is to apply the sizeof operator to an expression and expect the
expression to be evaluated. However the expression is not evaluated: sizeof only acts on the type
of the expression. To avoid this error, sizeof shall not be used on expressions that contain side
effects, as the side effects will not occur. sizeof() shall only be applied to an operand which is a
type or an object. This may include volatile objects. For example:
int32_t i;
int32_t j;
j = sizeof(i = 1234);
/* j is set to the sizeof the type of i which is an int */
/* i is not set to 1234.                                */
