a Boolean value.
No assignments are permitted in any expression which is considered to have a Boolean value.
This precludes the use of both simple and compound assignment operators in the operands of
a Boolean-valued expression. However, it does not preclude assigning a Boolean value to a
variable.
If assignments are required in the operands of a Boolean-valued expression then they must be
performed separately outside of those operands. This helps to avoid getting "=" and "==" confused,
and assists the static detection of mistakes.
See "Boolean Expressions" in the glossary.
For example write:
x = y;
if ( x != 0 )
{
foo();
}
and not:
if ( ( x = y ) != 0 )   /* Boolean by context */
{
foo();
}
